When, or by what means, the manuscript now in the British Museum came into the hands of Sir Robert Cotton, cannot now be ascertained. The Editor is inclined to think that by some accident it was carried off from Melrose at a periodis not anterior to, at least immediately after, the Reformation. Had it been preserved there when Viscount Haddington had a grant of the abbey-lands, it is probable that he would have preserved it along with the splendid collection of charters1 which came into his possession upon that occasion, or that some extracts from it would have been found in his “Collections of ¹ Charters, Evidents, and AntiquitieS,” now in the Advocates’
